[[File:Jean-Marc Nattier - Perseus, under the protection of Minerva, turns Phineus to stone by brandishing the head of Medusa.jpg|thumb|Nattier, ''Perseus petrifying Phineus'']]

In Book V of [[Ovid]]'s mock-epic ''[[Metamorphoses (poem)|Metamorphoses]]'', '''Athis''' is a young [[demigod]] from India, son of [[Limnaee]], a nymph of the [[Ganges]]. He was follower of [[Phineus (son of Belus)|Phineus]]. During a quarrel between [[Perseus]] and Phineus, Perseus killed Athis, who was preparing to shoot his bow, with a log that had been smoldering in the middle of the altar. The Assyrian Lycabas, wept for his fallen comrade, and attempted to avenge him, shooting an arrow at [[Perseus]] from Athis's bow. However, Perseus avoided the arrow, and Lycabas, too, fell.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ovid.lib.virginia.edu/trans/Metamorph5.htm|title=Metamorphoses (Kline) 5, the Ovid Collection, Univ. of Virginia E-Text Center|last=|first=|date=|website=ovid.lib.virginia.edu|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-10-13}}</ref>

