[[File:I Made Subandi 2013.jpg|thumb|I Made Subandi at the 2013 San Francisco Ethnic Dance Festival.]]
'''I Made Subandi''' (born February 1966, [[Batubulan]]<ref name="McGraw">McGraw, Andrew Clay (2005). ''Musik kontemporer: experimental music by Balinese composers'', p.362. Wesleyan University.</ref>) is a [[gamelan]] [[composer]] and performer from [[Gianyar Regency|Gianyar]], [[Bali]]. Having studied with his father, drummer and ''gender wayang'' player I Made Dig, and at SMKI ('85-'88) and [[Indonesian Institute of the Arts, Denpasar|STSI]] ('89-'93),<ref name="McGraw"/> he teaches at the [[Indonesian Institute of the Arts, Denpasar|Indonesian Academy of Performing Arts]] in Bali. In 1999, during his residency with [[Gamelan Sekar Jaya]], he composed a soundtrack for the 1933 silent film "[[Legong (film)|Legong Dance of the Virgins]]" with American composer [[Richard Marriott]], scored for Balinese gamelan, string quartet, trumpet and clarinet. He has collaborated with Dutch trio Boi Akih and American ensemble [[Club Foot Orchestra]]. He is well known for his use of experimentation. [[Michael Tenzer|Tenzer]] describes Subandi as one of a few composers who, "have achieved a self-conscious and fundamental break with the ''[[tabuh kreasi]]'' form of the recent past."<ref name="Tenzer">Tenzer, Michael (2000). ''Gamelan Gong Kebyar: The Art of Twentieth-Century Balinese Music'', p.371-2. University of Chicago Press. {{ISBN|9780226792835}}.</ref>

Compositions include ''Bajramusti'' (1997).<ref name="Tenzer"/> He has collaborated with Dutch trio [[Boi Akih]]. {{See LMST|Made|Subandi}}

