{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}
'''Patrick Cotter O'Brien''' (19 January 1760&nbsp;– 8 September 1806) was the first of only seventeen people in medical history to stand at a verified height of eight feet (2.44 m) or more. O'Brien was born in [[Kinsale]], [[County Cork]], Ireland. His real name was Patrick Cotter and he adopted O'Brien as his stage name in the [[sideshow|sideshow circus]], claiming descent from the legendarily gigantic [[Brian Boru]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|title=Mutants: On Genetic Variety and the Human Body|last=Leroi|first=Armand Marie|publisher=Penguin|year=2005|isbn=0142004820|location=|pages=177-178}}</ref> He was also known as the ''Bristol Giant'' and the ''Irish Giant''. Another giant of this period, [[Charles Byrne (giant)|Charles Byrne]], also claimed to be an O'Brien.<ref name=":0" />
It is believed that he died from the effects of the disease [[gigantism]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.irishpost.com/life-style/eight-facts-about-patrick-cotter-obrien-the-eight-foot-tall-irishman-who-died-in-1806-100510|title=Eight facts about Patrick Cotter O’Brien, the eight foot tall Irishman who died in 1806 {{!}} The Irish Post|last=Post|first=Irish|work=The Irish Post|access-date=2018-06-30|language=en-GB}}</ref>
No hearse could be found to accommodate his nine feet four inch casket encased in lead, and his remains were borne to the grave by relays of fourteen men. In his will, Cotter left £2,000 to his mother and a request that his body be entombed within twelve feet of solid rock (to prevent exhumation for scientific or medical research).<ref>{{cite book|last=Doherty|first=D.J. Hickey, J.E.|title=A dictionary of irish history 1800-1980|year=1989|publisher=Gill and Macmillan|location=Dublin|isbn=0-7171-1567-4|page=98|edition=[Paperback reprint]}}</ref>
In 1972 his remains were examined and it was determined that, while alive, he stood approximately 8 feet 1 inch (246&nbsp;cm) tall. This made him the tallest person ever at that time, a record that would be surpassed by the next 'eight-footer', [[John Rogan]], who died almost a century later. Patrick Cotter's giant boots are on display in the Kinsale Museum.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.westcorkpeople.ie/news/the-giant-of-kinsale-reveals-his-full-height-at-kinsale-museum/|title=West Cork People » The Giant of Kinsale reveals his full height at Kinsale Museum|website=www.westcorkpeople.ie|language=en|access-date=2018-06-30}}</ref>
An arm of Cotter's is currently preserved in the [[Hunterian Museum at the Royal College of Surgeons|Medical Museum of the Royal College of Surgeons]], London.{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}}
