{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2015}} {{Infobox person | name = Werner Koch | image = Werner Koch Portrait 01.2015-2.jpg | image_size = 180 | caption = Koch in 2015. | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1961|07|11}} | birth_place = [[Düsseldorf]], [[Germany]] | residence = [[Erkrath]], Germany | nationality = German | known_for = [[GNU Privacy Guard]] | education = | employer = | occupation = [[Software developer]] | home_town = | spouse = | children = | website = {{URL|http://werner.eifelkommune.de/}} }} '''Werner Koch''' (born July 11, 1961) is a German [[free software]] [[software developer|developer]].<ref name="wayner-new-york-times">{{cite news | url = http://partners.nytimes.com/library/tech/99/11/cyber/articles/19encrypt.html | date = November 19, 1999 | accessdate = February 6, 2015 | first = Peter | last = Wayner | newspaper = [[The New York Times]] | title = Germany Awards Grant for Encryption}}</ref> He is best known as the principal author of the [[GNU Privacy Guard]] (GnuPG or GPG).<ref name="angwin-propublica">{{cite web | url = https://www.propublica.org/article/the-worlds-email-encryption-software-relies-on-one-guy-who-is-going-broke | date = February 5, 2015 | accessdate = February 6, 2015 | first = Julia | last = Angwin | publisher = [[ProPublica]] | title = The World’s Email Encryption Software Relies on One Guy, Who is Going Broke}}</ref> He was also Head of Office and German Vice-Chancellor of the [[Free Software Foundation Europe]]. He is the winner of [[Award for the Advancement of Free Software]] in 2015 for founding GnuPG.<ref name=fsf2015>[https://www.fsf.org/news/library-freedom-project-and-werner-koch-are-2015-free-software-awards-winners Library Freedom Project and Werner Koch are 2015 Free Software Awards winners] FSF</ref>
Journalists and security professionals rely on GnuPG, and [[Edward Snowden]] used it to evade monitoring whilst he [[News leak|leaked]] [[classified information]] from the U.S. [[National Security Agency]].<ref name="goodin-ars">{{cite web | url = https://arstechnica.com/security/2015/02/once-starving-gnupg-crypto-project-gets-a-windfall-but-can-it-be-saved/ | date = 6 February 2015 | accessdate = 28 July 2015 | first = Dan | last = Goodin | publisher = [[Condé Nast]] | website = [[Ars Technica]] | title = Once-starving GnuPG crypto project gets a windfall. Now comes the hard part}}</ref>
==Life and work== Koch lives in [[Erkrath]], near [[Düsseldorf]], Germany. He began writing [[GNU Privacy Guard]] in 1997, inspired by attending a talk by [[Richard Stallman]] who made a call for someone to write a replacement for [[Phil Zimmermann]]'s [[Pretty Good Privacy]] (PGP) which was subject to [[Export of cryptography from the United States|U.S. export restrictions]].<ref name="angwin-propublica" /> The first release of GNU Privacy Guard was in 1999 and it went on to become the basis for most of the popular email encryption programs: GPGTools, [[Enigmail]], and Koch's own [[Gpg4win]], the primary free encryption program for [[Microsoft Windows]].<ref name="angwin-propublica" />
In 1999 Koch, via the [[German Unix User Group]] which he served on the board of,<ref name="angwin-propublica" /> received a grant of 318,000 marks (about $170,000 US) from the [[Federal Ministry of Economics and Technology (Germany)|German Federal Ministry of Economics and Technology]] to make GPG compatible with Microsoft Windows.<ref name="wayner-new-york-times" /> In 2005 he received a contract from the German government to support the development of [[S/MIME]].
Journalists and security professionals rely on GnuPG, and [[Edward Snowden]] used it to evade monitoring whilst he [[News leak|leaked]] [[classified information]] from the U.S. [[National Security Agency]].<ref name="goodin-ars"/> Despite GnuPG's popularity, Koch has struggled to survive financially, earning about $25,000 US per year since 2001<ref name="angwin-propublica" /> and thus considered abandoning the project and taking a better paying programming job.<ref name="goodin-ars" /> However, given Snowden's leaked documents showed the extent of NSA surveillance, Koch continued.<ref name="goodin-ars" /> In 2014 he held a funding drive and in response received $137,000 US in donations from the public,<ref name="angwin-propublica" /> and [[Facebook]] and [[Stripe (company)|Stripe]] each pledged to annually donate $50,000 US to GPG development.<ref name="angwin-propublica" /><ref name="thomson-the-register" /> Unrelated, in 2015 Koch was also awarded a one-time grant of $60,000 US from the [[Linux Foundation]]'s [[Core Infrastructure Initiative]].<ref name="thomson-the-register">{{cite news | url = https://www.theregister.co.uk/2015/02/05/gnupg_funding/ | date = 5 February 2015 | accessdate = 6 February 2015 | first = Iain | last = Thomson | newspaper = [[The Register]] | title = Internet lobs $$$s at dev of crucial GPG tool after he runs short of cash}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.linuxfoundation.org/news-media/blogs/browse/2015/02/answering-call-werner-koch-s-everywhere | date = 8 February 2015 | accessdate = 28 July 2015 | first = Jim | last = Zemlin | publisher = [[Linux Foundation]] | title = Answering the Call for Werner Koch’s Everywhere}}</ref>
